user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_NetworkGetID code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 14.3.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 14.3 is Controlling expressions shall not be invariant.
Here are exceptions to this rule:
1. Invariants that are used to create infinite loops are permitted.
2. A do-while loop with an essentially Boolean controlling expression that evaluates to false and satisfies the constraints and semantics for an integer constant expression is permitted.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_NetworkGetID.
```c
int32 OS_NetworkGetID(void)
{
    int32 IdBuf;

    /* always delegate to low-level API */
    if (OS_NetworkGetID_Impl(&IdBuf) != OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        /* return a hardcoded value on failure */
        return -1;
    }

    return IdBuf;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The controlling expression 'OS_NetworkGetID_Impl(&IdBuf) != OS_SUCCESS' is effectively invariant: OS_NetworkGetID_Impl always returns OS_SUCCESS (0), so the comparison is always false. This is not an infinite-loop or the permitted do-while constant-false case, so Rule 14.3 is violated.
</scenario>
